I think "The Wizard of Oz" would be particularly conductive to having a cult started off it, precisely because it was written with the intention of being a "rationalistic" denial of traditional folkloric fairy tales and something the young reader was not supposed to "believe" in.

On a low level, Oz grants a real heart to the Tinman and he is now a man with feelings. On a middle level, the reader knows it's all fake and just some silk and sawdust, placebo. On the top level, the silk heart worked. Oz fulfilled all of his promises. He really was a wizard.

The three layers of cults, as stated by an old associate: low level = sincere unquestioning belief, simpleton; middle level = ironic belief and actual disbelief, "knowing it's a joke" not believing that e.g. the leader is a god, etc.; top = sincere belief. It is all true.
